public class hello {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int i = 1;  // Initialize loop counter
        
        do  // Start of do-while loop
        {
            System.out.println("Hi"+i);  
            // Output in each iteration:
            // Hi1 (when i=1)
            // Hi2 (when i=2)
            // Hi3 (when i=3)
            // Hi4 (when i=4)
            
            i++;  // Increment counter: 1→2→3→4→5
        }
        while(i<=4);  // Condition check at bottom:
                      // Continues while i≤4 (stops when i=5)
    }
}

Complete Theory & Interview Concepts: Do-While Loop
1. Basic Structure:
java

do {
    // code block
} while(condition);

2. Key Characteristics:

    Post-test loop: Condition checked AFTER execution

    Guaranteed execution: Runs at least once even if condition is false initially

    Terminating semicolon: Note the ; after while(condition)

3. Execution Flow:

    Execute code block

    Check condition

    If true → repeat from step 1

    If false → exit loop

4. Comparison with While Loop:
Feature	do-while	while
Check Time	After first execution	Before first execution
Min Runs	At least 1	Possibly 0
Use Case	When you need to run code at least once	When code may not need to run at all
